      <div xml:id="NA134-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">iḵtu (ET: itu tamar) iṟceṟippār eṉa āṟṟāḷāya talaiviyai aḵtu ilar eṉpatupaṭat (G1+2: eṉapaṭat) tōḻi colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said to HER who did not have the strength thinking they would confine [her] to the house so that it was said that they would forgo that.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA134">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            iṉiti ṉiṉitu talaippaṭutu meṉpa</l>
<l>            titukol vāḻi tōḻi kātalar</l>
<l>            varukuṟi ceyta varaiyakac ciṟutiṉaic</l>
<l>            cevvāyp pāciṉaṅ kaṭiyar koṭicci</l>
<l>            yavvāyt taṭṭaiyō ṭavaṇai yākeṉa </l>
<l>            vēyaṇmaṉ yāyu nuntai vāḻiya</l>
<l>            rammā mēṉi niraitoṭik kuṟumakaḷ</l>
<l>            cellā yōniṉ muḷḷeyi ṟuṇkeṉa</l>
<l>            melliya viṉiya kūṟali ṉiyāṉaḵ</l>
<l>            tollēṉ pōla vuraiyā ṭuvalē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Does this say, oh friend,</l>
<l rend="indent">that something sweeter than sweet will happen to us?</l>
<l>Mother actually does not seem herself, saying:</l>
<l rend="indent">“be at that place with your pretty-mouthed Taṭṭai, creeper-girl,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">koṭicci</term> has to be taken here as a vocative of the 2nd person, which might have been a problem to mark morphologically on a word ending in -<term xml:lang="ta">i</term>.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">to chase away the red-beaked green groups from the little millet</l>
<l rend="indent">inside the mountains, where the sign for [his] coming was made</l>
<l rend="indent4">by [our] lover,”</l>
<l rend="indent4">and may your father live<note place="foot">It seems we have to read a complete chiasm here and construe <term xml:lang="ta">yāy</term> with <term xml:lang="ta">ēyaḷ</term> (marked as a finite form by <term xml:lang="ta">maṉ</term>) and <term xml:lang="ta">nuntai</term> with <term xml:lang="ta">vāḻiya</term>, although this results in an asyndetic coordination (mother did X and father may live).</note>, saying:</l>
<l rend="indent">“little daughter with bracelets in a row [and] pretty dark body,</l>
<l rend="indent3">please go. Let me eat your thorn teeth!<note place="foot">To eat one's teeth is clearly a metaphorical expression for kissing (cf. NA 17.6, 204.6).</note></l>
<l>While talking softly [and] pleasantly I’ll</l>
<l>act talking as if I were not content with that.</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
